<font color="#FF0000">30 YEARS AGO TODAY!</font><br>
<tt>Thu Nov 20 17:45:01 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
30 years ago today:<br>
During Operation Foster, Dai Loc Area, in the Arizona Territory;<br><br>
From Official Marine Corps Records:<br><br>
“D+7, 20 Nov 1967<br>
3rd Battalion, 7th Marines. Co I swept the area of contact on 19 Nov finding a pack, khaki uniform, documents, 20 fighting positions, blood pools and expended AK-47 and .30 cal cartridges in the vicinity of (AT 872524) Phu  Long (1). Ground activity was charactorized by light to moderate contact with Co I encountering as estimated 20 NVA in the vicinity of (870520) at 1615.” <br><br>
From my diary;<br>
Later that afternoon Aggie opened up with a sixty round burst from the M-60 machine gun. On a squad of gooks coming up a small trail toward the French Vile where we had set up in. <br><br>
At first we didn’t believe him, but then found the blood trails leading away in two different directions. Once we were out in the open crossing an open field following the blood trails we were ambushed. Aggie and I jumped on the wrong side, the side the enemy were on. We spent the next three hours out in the open until one of our platoons outflanked the entrenched North Vietnamese Communist soldiers. Three Marines from our platoon were wounded that day, Dumont, Gerald, Howard Robert W. and Hullihen, Ira. <br><br>
From Official Marine Corps Records:<br>
“A sweep of the area after the conduct of artillery and fixed wing missions uncovered large pools of blood.” <br>

